    	<div class="comment_content">
    		
<p>Emory University Hosp. located in the heart of Emory Uni. is over 100 years old. Most nurses, in that facility that has over some 450 beds and one of the oldest ER , will tell patients in wards like CCU, where open heart surgery patients wind up after one or two days in ICU, NOT to take baths or showers in facilities attached to rooms . that cost close to or over $5500 a night. Simply because the plumbing is unsafe as the water and the general sanitation. Even open heart surgery patients who stay in the CCU wards which has close to 50 plus rooms stay 8 to 10 days. Those who cannot take care of themselves or has no family etc are dumped into so called skilled nursing care facilities, where there is one RN, One PA and some 70 plus LVNs, most of who are low paid foreign. There are several such facilities, all part of the same Emory Health Care. All under the direction of one or two doctors, who specialize in geriatrics, all because they have have work 9 to 5 Monday-Friday as salaried physicians, with very general and limited range medical practice. For all other medical care these most elderly and many too many senile old folks are shuttled to various Clinics , that nothing more then profit centers. In fact the whole Emory Care System is run like an old Southern Plantation and that mentality. Where Medical School Department heads run herds.<br /> This over 100 years old Hospital in most CCU wards still have individual window air conditioners, that are keep at 65 degree’s F and nurses often use blankets to shut of cold air vents for patients who desire warmer and atmosphere.<br /> Emory no doubt may have two specially build isolation room, because next door to it is the CDC with an annual budget of some $12 billion a year, and it is indeed very desirable for patients with deadly Ebola virus.<br /> But considering the over all location and condition and age of the main Hospital, it is a sitting time bomb. I for one am sure that if the Joint Commission and CAP were to have a much closer look and a half way decent true and real inspection of the facility, it would be condemned on the spot. I for one do not take any pleasure in writing such report. Other then the facts I was a recent patient there and am an ex medical school professor.</p>

    	</div>



