    	<div class="comment_content">
    		
<p>Actions of the hospital staff are commendable but they are not risk-free and with this virus some of the risk is unknown.</p> 
<p>Most of the account of handling the ebola patients at Emory sound reasonable and appropriate but the devil’s in the details. Example: autoclaves are for sterilizing via steam under pressure, medical supplies e.g. surgical instruments which have been previously washed. So when it is reported that autoclaves were somehow used to treat waste materials that the waste disposal contractor would not accept – major red flag; this is one of the serious issues with treating infectious wastes. Incineration of “red bag” infectious wastes is generally standard practice as I understand it. This may require use of specialty disposal contractors.</p>

    	</div>



